<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / London Stock Exchange: SmithKline firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JEFFREY BROWN, STEVE THOMPSON and RAMRAJ GOGNA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The market decided that SmithKline Beecham had secured a good price for the
US over-the-counter arm of its recently acquired Sterling Health business.
The shares shrugged off interest rate concern to move up 7 1/2 before
closing 4 ahead at 425 1/2 p.
SmithKline sold the business to Bayer, of Germany, which some analysts
believed had been prepared to pay a premium for the emotional content of the
acquisition. The company, which invented aspirin, lost title in the US after
the First World War as a result of allied reparation demands.
Mr Robin Gilbert of Panmure Gordon had factored in between Dollars 600m and
Dollars 700m for the disposal and was surprised that it had achieved Dollars
1bn. He said the move would go a considerable way to dispersing the gloom
over SmithKline's gearing, which had leapt to a very high level following
the Dollars 2.7bn acquisition of the entire Sterling Health business.
</TEXT>
