<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Pendragon helped by revived demand for new
upmarket cars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A revival in demand for new upmarket cars lay behind a 32 per cent rise in
pre-tax profits to Pounds 4.06m at Pendragon, the executive and luxury car
dealer, in the six months to June.
Mr Trevor Finn, chief executive, explained that with used car values rising
towards the levels for new cars, people were more likely to buy new. New car
sales contributed Pounds 6.2m of gross profits, against Pounds 4.6m last
time.
He suggested that 'principals of industry' were giving signals that the
recession was now over and that they were making car purchases they had
previously postponed.
This, Mr Finn said, helped to explain why the group's total new
registrations grew by 20 per cent over last time, against a 14 per cent rise
in the whole car market.
Group turnover climbed 56 per cent from Pounds 119.6m to Pounds 186.9m,
including Pounds 2.46m from acquisitions. Growth in operating profits was
less dramatic at 39 per cent, from Pounds 3.57m to Pounds 4.94m, including
Pounds 68,000 from acquisitions.
Mr Ian Wheeler, finance director, said the margin slippage was due to the
addition of Ford, Peugeot and additional Rover franchises, which added
Pounds 25m turnover to last time's Pounds 5.5m in the group's EC volume car
sector. This greater turnover at smaller margin, he said, had a dilutive
effect across the group.
Gross profits from used car sales were flat at Pounds 2.2m, while after
sales business contributed Pounds 12.4 (Pounds 9.4m). Mr Finn said that
luxury cars owners were more likely to return to the seller than turn to
Kwik-Fit or the like. Contract hire chipped in Pounds 1.9m (Pounds 900,000),
illustrating the rise in values in the used car market.
Interest payable rose to Pounds 888,000 (Pounds 495,000) on borrowings up at
Pounds 13.4m (Pounds 8.2m at end-December).
The interim dividend is lifted to 2.7p (2.4p), payable from earnings up 20
per cent to 7.3p (6.1p) per share.
</TEXT>
