<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Soggy crisp prices and surfeit of pigs hold Dalgety to
Pounds 120m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lower UK crisp prices and an over-abundance of continental pigs limited
Dalgety, the food and agribusiness group, to a 7 per cent rise in pre-tax
profits to Pounds 120.1m for the year to June 30.
Without these setbacks, operating profits from continuing operations would
have risen about 10 per cent, Mr Richard Clothier, chief executive, said.
They fell 4 per cent to Pounds 124.9m, although acquisitions contributed a
further Pounds 9.6m to leave the group modestly ahead.
With both markets expected to show tentative signs of recovery this year,
however, Dalgety raised its final dividend from 12.65p to 13.15p a share.
Dalgety said it would seek more acquisitions in continental Europe, where it
was focusing on food ingredients and pet foods, while concentrating its
consumer foods efforts on the UK where it has strong brands such as Golden
Wonder Crisps.
In line with that strategy, it said yesterday it was selling the Dutch
savoury snack business to United Biscuits for Pounds 21m.
The UK crisp market enjoyed volume growth over the past year but wholesale
prices have fallen by at least 5 per cent, analysts estimate. Supermarkets
have exploited excess capacity, persuading manufacturers to produce
own-label snacks at low prices. Despite the pressures, Golden Wonder
products increased their market share to 18 per cent. Further cost cuts was
the key to improving profitability, Mr Clothier said.
Operating profits from foods fell 13 per cent to Pounds 57.4m despite good
performances from sauces and Spillers pet foods. The latter was boosted by
the acquisition of Paragon from British Petroleum.
Agribusiness operating profits rose 8 per cent to Pounds 34.8m. An animal
feed acquisition and a 24 per cent increase in US sales by Dalgety's Pig
Improvement Company offset low prices for its pigs in Europe. Food
ingredients lifted operating profits by 49 per cent to Pounds 57.4m thanks
to improved flour milling and acquisitions.
Food distribution in the US reported a 15 per cent rise in operating profits
to Pounds 16.4m, benefiting from higher sales to McDonald's and other
customers.
Group turnover rose 11 per cent from Pounds 4.47bn to Pounds 4.96bn. Pre-tax
profit of Pounds 120. lm was struck after a Pounds 2.8m charge for the
settlement of insurance claims. The 1992-93 figure of Pounds 112.2m included
a Pounds 9m provision for the same reason. Including the charges, earnings
per share were 36.7p against 35.7p. Acquisitions totalling Pounds 85m pushed
up net debt to Pounds 127m from Pounds 49m and gearing from 12 to 33 per
cent.
Lex, Page 22
Dutch disposal, Page 27
