<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Forte expected to beat Accor for Meridien hotels chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Forte, the UK hotels and restaurants group, is favoured to win its
long-running battle with Accor of France to gain control of Meridien, the
luxury hotels chain owned by Air France. The state-owned airline is expected
to make an announcement on Wednesday.
Hotel industry observers in London, however, were cautioning yesterday
against excessive optimism on Forte's behalf. They note that Accor used its
political influence in France to postpone a Forte victory before.
Accor lobbyists are believed to have stepped up their activities over the
past few days, arguing for the chain to remain in French hands. 'We know
they're going like fury,' one UK industry observer said yesterday.
Air France declined to comment on the sale of a controlling stake in
Meridien ahead of Wednesday's board meeting. But officials confirmed that a
decision had been taken based on the size of the relative offers. Forte's
offer values the hotel chain chain at FFr1.9bn while Accor's offer is
thought to value the company at FFr1.7bn.
Both offers represent an increase of FFr100m since the bids were first
tabled in April. A decision on the bids was delayed, after Accor lobbied the
centre-right government of French prime minister Mr Edouard Balladur.
Finance for Accor's offer is being provided by Prince Al-Waleed Bin Talaal
of Saudi Arabia. It is understood that the eventual winner's bid would be
reduced if Meridien lost a significant number of hotel management contracts
as a result of a change of ownership.
Air France, which is seeking to reduce its debt burden is expected to sell
the majority of its 57 per cent stake in the hotels chain. The European
Commission has ordered the completion of the sale by the end of this year as
a condition for a French state capital injection of FFr20bn for the
lossmaking airline.
Meridien's management has expressed its preference for the bid from Forte.
But some unions at the hotel chain are opposed to the sale and are planning
a demonstration at Air France today in protest at the move.
The Meridien group, which comprises 58 hotels, fell into loss last year. The
company blamed the losses, which totalled FFr29.7m, on difficult market
conditions, particularly in its French operations.
