<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Quebec separatists sweep to victory in provincial elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The separatist Parti Quebecois swept to victory in provincial elections in
Quebec yesterday, setting the stage for a divisive referendum on the future
of Canada's only French-speaking province.
However, with a number of returns still to be declared, it appeared the PQ's
victory might not reach the landslide proportions suggested by recent
opinion polls. An hour after the polls closed last night, the Canadian
Broadcasting Corporation said that PQ candidates were elected or leading in
80 of the 125 seats in the National Assembly.
The outgoing Liberals, who want Quebec to remain part of Canada and who had
won a clear majority in the 1989 election, were elected or leading in 45
constituencies. Opinion polls had projected PQ wins in 80 to 90 seats, with
no more than 40 seats for the Liberals.
Besides the Liberals' unexpectedly large number of seats, federalist forces
were encouraged by the early results, which suggested that the PQ would win
less than 50 per cent of the popular vote.
The PQ, led by former economics professor Mr Jacques Parizeau, has promised
to hold an independence referendum some time in 1995. But opinion polls have
consistently shown that a clear majority of Quebeckers is opposed to an
outright split from Canada. Political observers have concluded that many
voters turned to the PQ mainly to reflect their desire for a change in
government.
The PQ's last term in office, between 1976 and 1985, was marked by a
humiliating defeat in a 1980 referendum for a loose form of sovereignty. PQ
leaders have indicated that they plan to wage a much more vigorous
pro-independence campaign in the next referendum than they did 14 years ago.
One advantage they will have is the presence of a large group of separatist
MPs, belonging to the Bloc Quebecois, in the federal House of Commons in
Ottawa.
Mr Jean Chretien, Canada's prime minister and an avid federalist, was due to
make a statement on the election result late last night. In addition, the
premiers of the other nine provinces, who will play a crucial role in
shaping public opinion ahead of the referendum, are due to discuss their
strategy in a telephone conference call this morning.
</TEXT>
