<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's current affairs offerings look more promising than anything in the
drama and light entertainment categories, though ITV's half-hour police
drama, The Bill, maintains a high standard (8.00). BBC2 reports on the
increasingly tough, and increasingly American, attitude towards student
grants in the UK in Taken For Granted. Demanding that people 'work their
way' through university is fine when there are jobs to be had, but more
problematical during periods of high unemployment. Even with government
loans to students we now seem perilously close to a system which provides
higher education mainly for those with rich parents (7.20). Dirty Money
opened last week with a racy account of the (pretty fruitless) attempt to
reduce cocaine dealing by confiscating the suppliers' funds. Today's
programme (10.25 BBC1) is about the rapid growth of 'gangster capitalism' in
Russia where there seems to be little legislation to say what you can and
cannot do. ITV ends its exhaustive investigation of 'acquaintance rape' in
Network First with the actual trial. (10.40).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
