<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / UK Economy: Lift in rates increases Clarke's City stock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's personal stock among City analysts was one of
the clearest beneficiaries of yesterday's surprise base-rate rise. The
decision wrong-footed most of the market and provoked squeals from business
and industry but has lent credibility in the City to the government's
low-inflation creed.
Part of the reason for the favourable reception lies in the underlying
economics. With output growing fast and yesterday's producer price data
providing one of the first hints that inflationary pressures may be in the
pipeline, the government's argument that base rates must rise soon to avert
inflation has already been widely accepted in the City.
But the real reason for the positive verdict was more political than
statistical. In deciding to raise rates ahead of the Conservative party
conference, while most economic indicators suggest that consumer confidence
is fragile, Mr Clarke yesterday went part of the way towards convincing the
City that it is now economic factors, rather than short-term politics, that
are determining the timing of interest-rate rises.
Mr Geoffrey Dicks, UK economist with Natwest Markets said: 'It is a bold
move for the chancellor to go to the party conference with rates having
risen - indeed, to raise rates with inflation this low is probably
unprecedented.'
Mr David Mackie, UK economist at JP Morgan, said: 'To my mind this can only
improve the chancellor's reputation. This move suggests that although Norman
Lamont (the previous chancellor) outlined the inflation target as being 1
per cent to 4 per cent, the Bank of England and chancellor are now really
aiming for 1 per cent to 2.5 per cent.'
However, the verdict on the new system of monthly monetary meetings between
Mr Clarke and Mr Eddie George, the Bank governor, remains more mixed.
On the one hand, many analysts believe the greater openness leaves the Bank
with much of the credit for the rate rise. Mr Jeremy Hawkins, chief
economist in London at the Bank of America, said that the clear message of
yesterday's move is that the Bank 'has much more independence in setting
monetary policy than it has had in its history'.
On the other hand, the logistics of the move has prompted complaints that
the Bank's method for announcing a rise is unnecessarily opaque. The
complaints may partly reflect red faces in the City. After Bank money-market
operations last week - widely interpreted as confirming that interest rates
were unchanged - most economists were confident a rise had been postponed.
For some economists this pointed to an underlying weakness in the system.
One such was Mr Gavyn Davies, chief economist of Goldman Sachs who, like
many, predicted no rate change. He said: 'The fact that the decision was
delayed until Friday means that it is not being taken in the monetary
meeting and that is less credibility enhancing.'
Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Citibank, agreed. 'I don't see the
point of trying to catch the markets out,' he said.
Others say it highlights a broader change. Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist
with Salomon Brothers, said: 'The market has learnt that the process of
deciding a rate rise is not black and white . . . but from Mr Clarke's point
of view it helps to dampen the notion that interest-rate policy is still
politically driven.'
</TEXT>
