<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Clash on council reforms grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Local Government Commission yesterday intensified its opposition to the
government over local authority reform by proposing that the two-tier system
of districts and counties should remain unchanged in Gloucestershire.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, rejected this proposal when it
was first made, and said he would prefer to create new unitary all-purpose
authorities, which combine the functions of districts and counties.
But the commission, chaired by Sir John Banham, said it had found 'no
substantial new evidence' to alter its views. It had received only 111
submissions since the second review for the county was announced, 'many of
which repeated earlier representations'.
Sir John had already retained his proposals to keep the status quo in Durham
and Derbyshire, the other two counties where Mr Gummer called for a further
review.
The commission now seems likely to leave the two-tier status quo intact in
most of England. It has attempted to strengthen its opposition to the
government's agenda by holding 'advisory referenda' - as Sir John describes
them - in which all households in the counties concerned have been sent a
leaflet laying out a range of options.
Sir John made clear when announcing the first referendum, in Leicestershire,
that the commission would not recommend change if it was not strongly
supported. 'If there is not a clear message, our duty is to recommend no
change,' he said. 'We are not in the business of changing for its own sake -
nor is parliament.'
Results from Leicestershire, published yesterday, showed that only 2.3 per
cent of residents returned leaflets to the commission. Of these, 35 per cent
supported the commission's favoured option, which would give unitary status
to Leicester and Rutland while leaving two tiers for the rest of the county
untouched. At the same time 34 per cent expressed a preference for the
status quo, even though this was not an option formally presented by the
commission.
However, 60 per cent of Rutland residents who responded supported unitary
status for their district, which was an independent county until the last
local government reorganisation in 1974. Results for 11 more counties will
follow in the next few weeks.
Under the legislation which set up the review, the government has the power
to reject Sir John's recommendations, but it cannot order a change in
structure unless it has first been proposed by the commission.
This means the commission can block a unitary structure in England, even
though such systems have already been imposed on Wales and Scotland.
The commission has now made provisional recommendations for all the 39
counties in shire England. In 14 its preferred option is the status quo,
while in another 13 it has proposed unitary options while presenting the
status quo as an option.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
