<PROFILE>_AN-EIMDOACNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940913
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Howard accused on jail rule change
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Home Office told Whitemoor Prison, Cambridgeshire, not to body-search
visitors to IRA prisoners, the founder chairman of Whitemoor's Board of
Visitors claims today and she calls for the resignation of Mr Michael
Howard, the home secretary.
At the end of last week a prison guard at Whitemoor was shot when five
convicted IRA terrorists and an armed robber attempted to escape.
In letters published in several newspapers today Mrs Paddy Seligman says:
'The decision not to body-search visitors to IRA prisoners was made not
locally by management but at Home Office level. The implications resulting
from this decision are now obvious. If the resignation of anyone is called
for, it should be that of the home secretary.'
Mrs Seligman, who was a member of the board of visitors until March, said
the board had expressed concern about 'excessive privileges' given to
prisoners in dispersal prisons. 'Coupled with our concern about the sparsity
of searching of visitors to prisoners due to staffing level restrictions,
security is inevitably compromised.'
She says that custodial sentences must be available to protect the public in
certain cases but they are an expensive option which must be adequately
funded. Treasury economies must not preclude the protection of the public
and prison staff.
The escape attempt, after which two firearms were recovered, led to claims
by Ulster unionists that the IRA's ceasefire had broken down. However the
government made clear that it would have no effect on the peace process.
</TEXT>
