<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / IRA tune fails to slow tempo of City beat: The Square Mile's
tough-minded new police chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The IRA ceasefire is unlikely to mean a relaxation in the near future of
tough security measures introduced to protect the City after last year's
bomb attack, according to the City's new police commissioner, Mr William
Taylor.
In his first interview since his appointment in April, Mr Taylor underlined
the dangers of rushing to ease counter-terrorist measures which include
high-profile policing, roadblocks, a restrictive traffic scheme and
increasing video surveillance.
'This is a time for politicians to be talking. The business of policing will
come later. At this stage law enforcement should not be getting ahead of the
political situation,' he said.
Mr Taylor refused to be drawn on the political situation in Northern
Ireland, but said he felt 'entirely satisfied' that the continuing security
measures were 'proportionate' to the perceived threat.
Mr Taylor's views are thought to reflect the cautious attitude within the
security forces to the IRA ceasefire. It is understood that security
assessments of IRA intentions remain confused.
As well as being responsible for an area covering many potential terrorist
targets, Mr Taylor chairs the Association of Chief Police Officers' crime
committee and is the association's adviser on terrorism.
Mr Taylor, speaking at the City force's headquarters in Old Jewry, was
anxious that complacency in some political quarters about the intentions of
the IRA should not undermine the City's improved security, which has
involved increased co-operation between police and business. 'Crime of all
sorts in the City has tumbled and that is a consequence of a very real
partnership between police and the business community.'
The crime rate in the City fell 10 per cent last year and a further 17 per
cent in the first quarter of this year according to police figures.
Mr Taylor conceded that efforts to arrest and bring to trial those
responsible for last year's IRA Bishopsgate bomb attack had so far failed
because of lack of sufficient evidence.
But he claimed the fight against terrorism had become more efficient over
the past five years, with growing co-operation between regional police
forces and acceptance of the primacy of MI5, the security agency, in
intelligence-gathering. 'There is now a willingness to follow a lead in a
way that perhaps has been absent in the past.'
He spoke of 'a successful level of co-ordination and co-operation' between
police and MI5, but said he was not in favour of the creation of a new
national anti-terrorist unit or the extention of MI5's powers.
'Any suggestion of change has to be looked at very carefully and I would
imagine there would have to be a wide-ranging debate,' he said.
By contrast, Mr Taylor backs reform of the Serious Fraud Office and wants
the police to have a much clearer lead role in investigating financial
crime.
He welcomed the recommendation that the SFO's powers which remove the right
to silence and compel witnesses to answer questions be extended to the
police. At present such powers can only be used by SFO lawyers and
accountants. The recommendation comes from Mr John Graham - a senior
Treasury official who has conducted an inquiry into the SFO on behalf of Sir
Nicholas Lyell QC, the attorney-general.
Mr Taylor said a multi-disciplinary approach was necessary in some very big
fraud cases, but there was a need to re-examine the relationship between
police, lawyers and accountants 'so that we are not all fishing out of the
same pool'.
Echoing the tensions between police and non-police personnel in the SFO over
the management of investigations, Mr Taylor said: 'Investigation and
prosecution of fraud has been rather more successful than has sometimes been
portrayed but we have to deal with people's negative perceptions.  The key
is to harness people's skills to the best advantage and I think we should be
leading the investigations.'
Mr Taylor, 47, is widely regarded as one of the brightest and most
opinionated of police chiefs.
Although his area of London has not been marked out by the prime minister
for his attacks on the nation's 'yob culture', Mr Taylor insisted yesterday
on contributing to the debate, claiming that aspects of the criminal-justice
system still favoured the offender at the expense of the victim, and calling
for increased police powers.
He urges more effective use of a national DNA database, and greater
limitations on the right to silence.
</TEXT>
