<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Call for body to probe Bar complaints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A complaints bureau to investigate allegations of unsatisfactory work by
barristers which could order compensation payments to clients of up to
Pounds 2,000 should be established, the Bar Standards Review Body
recommended yesterday.
The recommendation was one of a number made by the review body, set up by
the Bar Council after last year's royal commission on criminal justice drew
attention to the poor performance of some barristers and called for a
raising of standards.
The complaints bureau, the review body suggests, should be run by a
non-barrister. It should have the power to demand apologies, order
compensation and refer cases to the Bar disciplinary tribunal.
If the Bar agrees to the establishment of such a bureau it could be in
operation by the start of 1996. It would cost about Pounds 167,000 a year to
run, said Lord Alexander of Weedon QC, chairman of the review body.
However, he stressed yesterday that the review body's other recommendations
were aimed at improving the standards of barristers' work so that complaints
were less likely. 'Prevention is still better than cure,' he said.
The other recommendations include pre-trial conferences to improve early
preparation of cases, publication by barristers' chambers of their working
procedures and fees, and the compulsory continuation of education during the
first three years of practice on issues such as case management, time
manage-ment and racial aware-ness.
</TEXT>
