<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Walker denies 'bogus' film deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Brent Walker's film division was never involved in bogus transactions, Mr
George Walker, the former chairman and chief executive of the property and
leisure company, said at the Old Bailey yesterday.
Beginning his second week in the witness box, Mr Walker strongly denied
prosecution allegations that he had helped inflate Brent Walker's profits by
illegally removing money from the company and then falsely declaring it as
income from sales of film rights.
Mr Walker and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, a former Brent Walker finance director,
both deny charges of theft, false accounting and conspiracy to falsify
accounts.
Cross-examined by Mr Peter Rook QC, Mr Walker agreed that until 1989, Brent
Walker had successively reported increased profits. However, he denied Mr
Rook's suggestion that, had the film division's accounts been properly
reported, this would have had a 'devastating effect'.
'If I had dropped dead, it would have had a devastating effect,' Mr Walker
replied.
Mr Rook then suggested that the reason some staff in the film division had
never heard of some of the transactions involving Universal Talent
Management, a company run by Mr John Quested, the managing director of the
film division, was because they were bogus. Mr Walker said the auditors
would have spotted bogus transactions.
Mr Walker did agree that he had signed documents related to some of the
transactions but denied he had detailed knowledge of the deals. He largely
relied upon Mr Quested to handle them, he said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
