<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / ITC to rule on late data service bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission will decide on Thursday if it should
grant a data broadcasting licence to a News International company in spite
of the application arriving nine minutes after deadline.
Mr Justin Cadbury, chief executive of Simple Active, a company controlled by
the Guardian Media Group, said last night he would consider seeking a
judicial review if the ITC accepts the bid from Skytext.
Mr Cadbury said he was present at ITC just before the noon deadline after
delivering what he thought was the only bid for an additional commercial
service. The licence is for use of spare lines on the ITV picture - but the
service is for only the professional transfer of data and not open for a
general audience.
Mr Cadbury said that at 17 seconds to the noon deadline Mr Anthony Hewitt,
ITC deputy secretary, began a countdown. Fifteen seconds later a message was
passed to Mr Hewitt saying another bid was on the way.
Mr Cadbury said: 'As we left, we saw a motorcyclist arrive. He signed the
visitors' book at 12.09.'
Simple Active bid Pounds 78,000 a year for the data licence. Skytext bid
Pounds 355,000. In normal circumstances the licence goes to the highest
bidder.
</TEXT>
