<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Taxman says there are dogs and dogs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Household dogs must continue to pay value added tax on their food, but
greyhounds can now get their nourishment tax-free, Customs &amp; Excise said
yesterday.
The department has laid down strict guidelines which will allow greyhound
owners to buy feed specifically designed for racing dogs free of VAT.
The decision follows a ruling by the VAT Tribunal which rejected Customs'
argument that greyhound feed should be treated in the same way as pet food
and be subject to VAT at the standard rate.
Customs has now agreed that greyhound feed - like most food for humans  -
will be zero-rated because greyhounds are working animals.
However, to qualify it must be 'a complete feed providing all the required
elements for a balanced diet for a dog'.
The same circular from Customs yesterday made a number of related rulings on
animals and VAT, some of them surprisingly exotic. Purchase of ostriches,
which was previously VAT-free, will now be standard-rated.
Customs said it maintained its position that while grass seed is zero-rated
because it is used as animal feed, pre-germinated seeds were designed for
commercial purposes and should be subject to VAT.
However, it said that because pre-germinated grass seed was widely
zero-rated within the industry at present, it would allow the practice of
exemption to continue 'for the time being'.
</TEXT>
