<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / World Bank backing for investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The World Bank has approved a proposal to use its financial might to boost
flows of private sector finance to projects in the developing world.
The board voted to use the bank's guarantee authority to offer investors
insurance against the risk of governments changing their policies - a risk
which has inhibited investors' willingness to put their money in developing
nation projects.
The decision will allow the bank to offer guarantees routinely, and to offer
them on a stand-alone basis when it is not co-financing a project.
The move marks a step in the World Bank's efforts to expand its involvement
in the private sector. Although all its policy advice to governments in the
developing world urges the virtues of privatisation and private sector
capital, the bank itself is bound by its articles to lend only to
governments or state institutions.
Although the bank's International Finance Corporation subsidiary invests in
the private sector, and its Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency
provides insurance mostly for equity investments, both have limited
resources; the bulk of the group's financial muscle is in the main bank.
An influential report this year from the Bretton Woods commission convened
by Mr Paul Volcker, former chairman of the US Federal Reserve Board, said
that 'of the challenges facing the World Bank Group, none is greater than
adapting to a world that has turned from public sector dominance towards
private enterprise and free markets'.
But bank officials say private investors are often wary governments may
change the rules: if they have funded an electricity plant, for example,
will the government regulator stop them selling power at market prices?
The World Bank has been experimenting with its guarantee power in some of
its co-financing operations. In the Dollars 1.8bn (Pounds 1.16bn) Hub River
power project in Pakistan, for example, the bank has guaranteed commercial
lenders against some risks, such as the possibility that the government
might not fulfil its obligation to provide fuel and to distribute the power
generated.
</TEXT>
