FT  13 SEP 94 / Lone pilot crashes at White House
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The pilot of the aircraft that crashed on a White House lawn early
yesterday, after penetrating high-security air space, had 'a history of
mental illness', investigators said, Reuter reports from Washington.
A US secret service spokesman identified the pilot, who died in the crash,
as Frank Eugene Corder, aged 38, of no fixed address. The single-engined
Cessna had been stolen from the county airport at Harford, Maryland, about
50 miles from Washington.
President Bill Clinton, his wife Hillary and their daughter Chelsea were
asleep a few hundred yards away across Pennsylvania Avenue in Blair House, a
guest residence, when the aircraft crashed at about 2am, sliding against the
White House. The family has moved out of the mansion while repairs are made.
A witness said that the aircraft's engine had been switched off. The
aeroplane swooped from the direction of the Washington Monument and passed
over a high, steel-rail fence before ploughing into the White House lawn.
