<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Germany ready to defy EU on telecom liberalisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany may allow new telecommunications companies to open their own
networks by the end of 1997, despite strong opposition from state-owned
Deutsche Telekom and national operators in other European Union countries.
In a surprise about-turn, Mr Wolfgang Botsch, post office minister, said
Bonn would consider going it alone if the EU's council of ministers failed
to fix a date for liberalising all EU networks by the end of this year.
A report earlier this year by the EU's Bangemann group on the development of
'information superhighway' services said competition in the provision of
networks was essential to Europe's future competitiveness with the US and
Japan.
The Commission is currently drafting proposals, to be published early next
year, which would open telecoms network infrastructure to competition at the
same time as telecoms services.
Basic phone services are set to be opened to competition in January 1998
across most of the EU. That would also become the date for infrastructure
competition if EU ministers support the Commission.
A Commission official said Mr Botsch's statement was an 'important first
step' towards persuading vested interests - notably state-owned telecoms
companies - to accept the inevitability of early infrastructure competition.
Mr Botsch, who had previously insisted the 12 EU states should move together
and grant open access to networks one or two years after the 1998 services
deadline, said Deutsche Telekom needed to be able to plan clearly.
Although accepting that other member states would be defensive, he was now
inclined to give up both monopolies simultaneously, he told the Frankfurter
Allgemeine Zeitung.
However, the move is still strongly opposed by Deutsche Telekom, which is
preoccupied with the privatisation of the company due to start in early
1996.
Mr Rolf-Dieter Leister, chairman of Deutsche Telekom's supervisory board,
told the Suddeutsche Zeitung: 'I certainly do not represent the view that
Germany should become the front-runner in European telecoms liberalisation.'
Mr Leister, Telekom's most senior non-executive, made plain that Telekom
management, preparing for the transition to a joint stock company next
January, was hampered by the need for all important decisions to be approved
at the political level.
Telekom's mandate had to be made clear now for the benefit of future
shareholders, he said. It was especially important that the enterprise
should be able to establish foreign subsidiaries and appoint top managers
without Mr Botsch's having the final say.
Meanwhile management needed to be clear on the scope and timing of domestic
liberalisation moves: 'Will the minister license corporate networks? How
will he deal with alternative networks? What will happen with broad-band
cable? How will mobile telephones develop in future?' he asked.
Telekom is especially anxious about pressure on the minister from power
utilities who want licences to start using their internal systems in 1996 to
offer data transmission services to the public and other industries,
effectively breaching Telekom's network monopoly.
The UK has allowed competition in telecoms infrastructure for a decade, and
the Netherlands is set to follow suit following the partial privatisation of
its state operator earlier this year.
</TEXT>
