<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Mortgage lenders raise cost of loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two of the UK's largest mortgage lenders - Nationwide Building Society and
Abbey National - responded to the base rate rise with increases in their
variable home loan rates. Many other lenders signalled they would be
announcing rises shortly.
As they did so, a range of organisations and associations, including estate
agents, housebuilders and lenders themselves, expressed anxiety that the
increase would damage the uncertain recovery in the housing market. Halifax
Building Society, the UK's largest mortgage lender, said an increase in its
rates was 'almost inevitable'. It plans to make an announcement within the
week.
But Woolwich Building Society, the UK's third largest, said the base rate
increase should not result in an increase in its mortgage and investment
rates. Mr Peter Robinson, Woolwich managing director, described the rises
from other lenders as 'a regrettable knee jerk reaction'.
Mr Adrian Coles, director-general of the Council of Mortgage Lenders, said
that at the very least the interest rate rise put back any recovery in the
housing market until next year.
However, individual organisations within the council, which represents
banks, societies and other lenders, were divided about how the rise would
affect the housing market.
Mr Brian Davis, chief executive of Nationwide, the UK's second - largest
society, which raised its basic variable rate by 0.4 per cent, said that as
the increase was expected at some point, he hoped it would not have too much
impact.
At Abbey National, which announced a 0.35 per cent rise in its standard
variable rate, Mr Charles Toner, managing director of the group's retail
division, similarly sought to play down the effect of the rise. But Halifax
said the rate rise would certainly damage confidence, and other lenders said
the timing - at the start of the important autumn sales period - was
particularly unfortunate. This gloomier view was reflected by Ocea, an
organisation representing 26 of the largest corporate estate agency chains.
Meanwhile, shares of house builders who had reported a rise in in new house
sales in August fell yesterday. Barratt fell 14p to 197, Beazer Homes fell
6p to 139p while Wilson Bowden shares dropped 11p to 397p.
</TEXT>
