<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 94 / Chancellor rules out prospect of early tax cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke yesterday dismissed any prospect of tax cuts in his
November Budget despite the shadow cast over next month's Conservative party
conference by the rise in interest rates.
In a move that will dash remaining hopes among Tory MPs of a significant
upturn in the government's political fortunes this autumn, Mr Clarke said
there was 'no chance' of lower taxes while the government was borrowing
Pounds 30bn a year.
Yesterday's base rate rise and the chancellor's curt rejection of recent
speculation that he might find room for a small income tax cut clashed
awkwardly with the launch of the agenda for the annual party conference.
Mr Jeremy Hanley, the party chairman, inadvertently showed his anxiety about
the impact on Tory morale by voicing hopes that there would be no further
increase in borrowing costs.
Still unsettled by the political row following his weekend 'gaffe' over law
and order, Mr Hanley broke with the carefully scripted official response to
comment: 'What we have to do is make sure that this interest rate rise is
it.'
With the Tories trailing Labour by more than 30 points in the opinion polls,
the conference agenda reflects growing discontent among local activists over
the government's handling of the economy.
It includes a series of demands from constituency associations for tax cuts
and the scrapping of the planned doubling next April of value added tax on
domestic fuel.
Ministers acknowledged that the strength of the recovery shown by the latest
batch of indicators has yet to be reflected in a 'feel-good' factor among
voters.
Their fear is that higher interest rates and the round of further tax rises
due in the coming months will further damage the government's standing.
But Mr Clarke, in characteristically robust form at a Treasury press
conference, coupled a reaffirmation of the government's medium-term
commitment to lower taxation with a rejection of any early tax cuts.
He acknowledged that public borrowing this year might be below the
Treasury's latest Pounds 36bn forecast, but said it was still expected to be
more than Pounds 30bn. Against that background, 'talk of tax reductions in
November is hopelessly premature. No chance'.
Some ministerial colleagues believe the chancellor was pushed into his rate
move by Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England. They want Mr
Clarke to take a stronger line against the bank's 'over-cautious' stance.
</TEXT>
