<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / International Company News: Globex rival faces further delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The launch of the Chicago Board of Trade's answer to Globex, an after-hours
computer trading system known as Project A, has been delayed again. The
system is now expected to make its debut the third week in September.
The CBoT, which is home to the actively traded US Treasury bond futures and
options markets, pulled the plug on Globex, the electronic futures trading
network owned by Reuters and operated jointly by the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and Matif, last May.
Since then, it has announced ambitious plans to link its own Project A
system with other after-hours computers in London and Australia.
However, the exchange has had difficulty getting the product launched on its
own turf. Originally scheduled to open trading on August 1, Project A was
delayed at the request of some CBoT members, who wanted a complete system
audit.
Deloitte &amp; Touche, the international accountancy firm, gave the system a
clear report in late August. Now, the CBoT is waiting for its regulator, the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission to review the auditor's report and give
its approval for the Project A launch.
The exchange already meets much of the demand for its products outside the
US time zone with its evening open-outcry trading session, which last month
had turnover of 229,510 contracts.
When Project A is launched it will initially open for only two hours in the
afternoon, bridging the gap between the close of the CBoT's afternoon
session and the opening of its evening session.
</TEXT>
