<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Company News (This Week): Buy-out teams could push bids past
Dollars 1bn - Western Union
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The final round of bidding in the auction of Western Union this Friday could
well elicit an offer of more than Dollars 1bn (Pounds 600m) for the world's
biggest non-bank money-transfer company - more than twice the first bid made
in June.
Three bidders remain in the ring: First Financial Management, a data
processing company, First Data, a credit card processing company, and
Forstmann Little, a leveraged buy-out firm.
Western Union, which handled 18.5m payment transactions last year, was put
up for auction by a US bankruptcy judge in June. The company, though not
itself in bankruptcy, is owned by New Valley, which has been operating under
Chapter 11 of the US bankruptcy code since March.
First Financial, which was the last of the bidders to declare an interest in
Western Union, appears to have made the most attractive offer so far. In the
first round of formal bidding, which closed 10 days ago, the data processing
company offered to pay Dollars 800m.
This compares with Dollars 970m from Forstmann Little - though unlike First
Financial, it has said it will not assume the company's unfunded pension
liability, put at Dollars 265m. First Data, seems to have dropped out of
contention by refusing to raise its earlier offer of Dollars 660m (plus
assumption of the pension liability).
</TEXT>
