<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Balladur plans review of white-collar crime probes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime minister, has begun a review of the
legal process for investigating white-collar crime following the recent wave
of probes into prominent industrialists.
The premier, speaking on television yesterday, said the recent spate of
highly-publicised investigations had been 'no good for democracy, for the
economy or for the companies themselves'. He did not envisage launching an
Italian-style 'clean hands' operation but said he was anxious to ensure that
the legal system was working efficiently.
Last week, a French magistrate opened an investigation into Mr Jean-Louis
Beffa, chairman of the Saint-Gobain glass group, as part of a probe into
alleged illicit political funding, and a Brussels judge issued an
international warrant for the arrest of Mr Didier Pineau-Valencienne,
chairman of the Schneider electrical engineering company.
At least another 100 heads of businesses are currently under investigation.
A poll published last week in Le Monde found that two-thirds of company
chairmen believed corruption was rife in the corporate sector. Mr Balladur
said last night that he believed 'none should be above the law'.
However, the government is understood to be concerned about the impact of
the investigations into confidence in the companies and their share prices.
Mr Francois Ceyrac, former chairman of the Patronnat, the employer's
association, and Mr Andre Bergeron, former director of the Force Ouvriere
trade union, will conduct the review.
The prime minister also announced that he plans next month to launch a new
series of initiatives to help young people following the completion of a
government survey of French youth triggered by this winter's youth riots. He
said he was also considering proposals to tackle long-term unemployment.
These initiatives come at a time when Mr Balladur is gaining ground in the
opinion polls in the run-up to next spring's presidential elections. He
topped a poll in yesterday's Journal du Dimanche as the most popular
presidential choice with 19 per cent of the votes, ahead of Mr Jacques
Delors, the leading left-wing contender, with 17 per cent. Mr Jacques
Chirac, the prime minister's rival for the centre-right ticket, scored 13
per cent.
Mr Balladur's popularity has been boosted by the withdrawal from public life
of Mr Francois Mitterrand, the socialist president, following prostate
surgery earlier this summer. The prime minister has since been able to adopt
a presidential role, notably in foreign affairs.
However, Mr Mitterrand last week criticised Mr Balladur for trying to usurp
him. The president, dogged by controversy over a book revealing his youthful
links with Nazi collaborators, is this evening expected to try to reassert
his authority when interviewed on television.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9222 Legal Counsel and Prosecution.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
