<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / The Lex Column: Mobile satellites
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A game of chicken is being played out in the so far non-existent market for
pocket satellite phones. Inmarsat's decision to raise Dollars 1bn (Pounds
600m) in equity for its mobile satellite affiliate has sharply increased the
game's stakes. The industrial might now converging on the market is
formidable. Inmarsat itself is owned by 75 telecom operators. Three rival
consortia include corporate giants such as Motorola, Lockheed, Sony, Loral,
Alcatel-Alsthom, Vodafone and France Telecom as well as Mr Bill Gates and Mr
Craig McCaw, America's best-known high-technology entrepreneurs.
Pocket satellite phones will be a niche market, providing services for
globe-trotting business people and those parts of the world without ordinary
cellular networks. That could still be a lucrative market. But it is
doubtful that four groups investing Dollars 10bn-20bn in total can all be
profitable. Some will back down or merge. The first test will be whether
they are prepared to put in hard cash.
Motorola's Iridium has already raised Dollars 800m, though some of this
involves commitments to provide services rather than cash. Loral's
Globalstar has pulled in a more modest Dollars 275m. Inmarsat's Dollars 1bn
financing is the most ambitious. But perhaps it has the easiest task, in
that it is raising the money from a closed group of mainly state-owned
monopolies. Inmarsat's plans will only look commercial to outsiders if its
few private-sector investors such as BT think the project worth bankrolling.
</TEXT>
